-- Power Prices Rise in Northeast as Demand Creeps Above Forecasts
-- B y   N a u r e e n   S .   M a l i k
-- 2013-09-18T16:32:29Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-09-18/power-prices-rise-in-northeast-as-demand-creeps-above-forecasts.html
Spot wholesale electricity rose
from New York to  Maine  as demand moved above forecasts.  While temperatures across the Northeast will be below
normal for a fifth day, readings will be higher than yesterday,
according to AccuWeather Inc. in  State College , Pennsylvania.
The high in  Manhattan  today may reach 72 degrees Fahrenheit (22
Celsius), 2 below normal, after dropping yesterday to 10 lower
than average to 65 degrees.  Spot prices in  New York City  rose $3.21, or 11 percent, to
$33.57 a megawatt-hour during the hour ended at 11 a.m. from the
same time yesterday, grid data compiled by Bloomberg showed.
Boston gained $3.40, or 12 percent, to $32.81.  The premium for Boston on-peak power versus New York
widened to $3.40 from 51 cents yesterday.  Demand on the six-state New England grid will increase to
15,850 megawatts from yesterdayâ€™s high of 15,729 megawatts, ISO
New England Inc. said in a  report  today.  The New York Independent System Operator Inc. expects power
consumption on the state grid to peak at 19,400 megawatts today
after sliding to 19,288 megawatts yesterday, which was the
lowest level since May 27.  Prices slumped on the 13-state PJM Interconnection LLC
network, which stretches from the mid-Atlantic states to the
Ohio Valley, as demand fell below forecast.  Spot power at its benchmark Western hub, which includes
deliveries to Washington, dropped $1.30, or 4.2 percent, to
$29.46 a megawatt-hour during the hour ended at 11 a.m.  To contact the reporter on this story:
